## Issues Encountered and Resolved

### Issue 1 — OPNsense Not Running (Destination Host Unreachable)

**Symptom:** Ping from Wazuh to OPNsense returned "Destination Host Unreachable" immediately after static IP was configured.

**Root Cause:** OPNsense was not running. All lab connectivity depends on OPNsense being the first VM started. Without OPNsense, no gateway exists and no Layer 3 routing is possible.

**Resolution:** Always start OPNsense first and wait for it to fully boot before starting any other VM.

**Lab Startup Order:**
| Order | VM | Wait For |
|-------|----|---------|
| 1st | OPNsense | Web GUI accessible |
| 2nd | Wazuh | Console login prompt |
| 3rd | Windows / Ubuntu | Desktop or login prompt |

---

### Issue 2 — OPNsense Had Conflicting HA and Multi-WAN Configuration

**Symptom:** Using the OPNsense Master VM from EP5 caused IP conflicts and routing issues due to leftover CARP VIPs, pfSync, and Multi-WAN gateway group configuration.

**Resolution:** Switched to the OPNsense Failover VM and cleaned up the following before starting the Wazuh lab:

| Item | Action |
|------|--------|
| WAN2 interface | Removed |
| Gateway Group (GW_Group) | Deleted |
| Policy routing LAN rules | Deleted |
| Block HTTP/HTTPS/QUIC rules | Deleted |
| Outbound NAT | Reset to Automatic |
| pfSync | Confirmed disabled |
| LAN IP | Confirmed 10.200.200.254/24 |

Removing the Block HTTP, HTTPS, and QUIC rules was critical — they would have prevented browser access to the Wazuh dashboard on port 443.

---

### Issue 3 — Wazuh Could Not Ping OPNsense or Windows (Asymmetric Connectivity)

**Symptom:** Windows could ping Wazuh and access the dashboard, but Wazuh could not ping OPNsense or Windows. ARP table on Wazuh correctly showed MAC addresses for both.

**Root Cause:** Expected asymmetric behavior. Windows Firewall blocks inbound ICMP from non-domain Linux hosts by default. OPNsense does not respond to ICMP directed at itself from LAN in some configurations.

**Resolution:** No fix required. ARP resolution confirmed Layer 2 connectivity. The Wazuh dashboard loading over HTTPS confirmed full service-level connectivity. Ping is not a reliable connectivity test in mixed OS environments.

---

### Issue 4 — Windows Could Not Reach Internet (LAN Rule Disabled)

**Symptom:** PowerShell failed to download the Wazuh agent with "remote name could not be resolved: packages.wazuh.com". Windows could not ping 8.8.8.8. DNS queries timed out even when directed at OPNsense.

**Root Cause:** The Default allow LAN to any firewall rule in OPNsense was disabled. This single rule controls all outbound traffic from every LAN device. When disabled it silently blocks all routing, NAT, and DNS for all clients simultaneously.

**Resolution:** Re-enabled the Default allow LAN to any rule in Firewall > Rules > LAN.

This is the third instance in this lab where a single disabled OPNsense firewall rule caused complete silent network failure across all clients. Rule state should always be verified first when clients suddenly lose connectivity.

